Question: Can you find out which store has the highest revenue and who runs it?
Generated SQL Query:
WITH store_revenue AS (
    SELECT 
        store_id, 
        SUM(amount) as total_revenue
    FROM payment
    GROUP BY store_id
),
max_revenue_store AS (
  SELECT store_id FROM store_revenue ORDER BY total_revenue DESC LIMIT 1
)
SELECT 
    s.store_id,
    st.first_name || ' ' || st.last_name AS manager_name,
    sr.total_revenue
FROM store s
JOIN max_revenue_store mrs ON s.store_id = mrs.store_id
JOIN staff st ON s.manager_staff_id = st.staff_id
JOIN store_revenue sr ON s.store_id = sr.store_id;
Expected SQL Query:
SELECT 
    s.store_id, 
    CONCAT(st.first_name, ' ', st.last_name) AS manager_name, 
    SUM(p.amount) AS total_revenue
FROM 
    store s
JOIN staff st ON s.manager_staff_id = st.staff_id
JOIN inventory i ON s.store_id = i.store_id
JOIN rental r ON i.inventory_id = r.inventory_id
JOIN payment p ON r.rental_id = p.rental_id
GROUP BY 
    s.store_id, manager_name
ORDER BY 
    total_revenue DESC
LIMIT 1;

Question: Which expensive-to-replace movies are also in the top five most popular categories?
Generated SQL Query:
WITH popular_categories AS (
    SELECT 
        category_id, 
        COUNT(*) AS film_count
    FROM film_category
    GROUP BY category_id
    ORDER BY film_count DESC
    LIMIT 5
)
SELECT 
    f.film_id, 
    f.title
FROM film f
JOIN film_category fc ON f.film_id = fc.film_id
JOIN popular_categories pc ON fc.category_id = pc.category_id
ORDER BY f.rental_rate DESC;
Expected SQL Query:
WITH top_categories AS (
    SELECT 
        fc.category_id, 
        COUNT(r.rental_id) AS rental_count
    FROM 
        film_category fc
        JOIN inventory i ON fc.film_id = i.film_id
        JOIN rental r ON i.inventory_id = r.inventory_id
    GROUP BY 
        fc.category_id
    ORDER BY 
        rental_count DESC
    LIMIT 5
),
top_films AS (
    SELECT 
        f.film_id, 
        f.title, 
        f.replacement_cost, 
        c.name AS category_name
    FROM 
        film f
        JOIN film_category fc ON f.film_id = fc.film_id
        JOIN category c ON fc.category_id = c.category_id
        JOIN top_categories tc ON fc.category_id = tc.category_id
    ORDER BY 
        f.replacement_cost DESC
)
SELECT * FROM top_films;

Question: Which two actors have appeared in the most movies together?
Generated SQL Query:
WITH actor_pairs AS (
    SELECT 
        fa1.actor_id AS actor1_id, 
        fa2.actor_id AS actor2_id, 
        COUNT(*) AS films_together
    FROM 
        film_actor fa1
        JOIN film_actor fa2 ON fa1.film_id = fa2.film_id
    WHERE 
        fa1.actor_id < fa2.actor_id
    GROUP BY 
        fa1.actor_id, fa2.actor_id
    ORDER BY 
        films_together DESC
    LIMIT 1
)
SELECT 
    a1.first_name || ' ' || a1.last_name AS actor1,
    a2.first_name || ' ' || a2.last_name AS actor2
FROM 
    actor_pairs ap
    JOIN actor a1 ON ap.actor1_id = a1.actor_id
    JOIN actor a2 ON ap.actor2_id = a2.actor_id;

Question: Which movies are among the top 10% highest earners?
Generated SQL Query:
WITH film_revenue AS (
    SELECT 
        f.film_id, 
        f.title, 
        SUM(p.amount) AS total_revenue
    FROM 
        film f
        JOIN inventory i ON f.film_id = i.film_id
        JOIN rental r ON i.inventory_id = r.inventory_id
        JOIN payment p ON r.rental_id = p.rental_id
    GROUP BY 
        f.film_id, f.title
),
revenue_percentile AS (
  SELECT 
        PERCENTILE_CONT(0.9) WITHIN GROUP (ORDER BY total_revenue) OVER () as top_10_percentile
    FROM film_revenue
)

Question: Can you find the longest and shortest rental period movies for each genre?
Generated SQL Query:
WITH film_rental_duration AS (
  SELECT
    c.name AS genre,
    f.rental_duration,
    f.title
  FROM
    category c
  JOIN film_category fc ON c.category_id = fc.category_id
  JOIN film f ON fc.film_id = f.film_id
),
genre_max_min AS (
  SELECT
    genre,
    MAX(rental_duration) AS max_rental_duration,
    MIN(rental_duration) AS min_rental_duration
  FROM
    film_rental_duration
  GROUP BY
    genre
)
SELECT
  g.genre,
  (SELECT title FROM film_rental_duration WHERE rental_duration = g.max_rental_duration AND genre = g.genre LIMIT 1) as longest_movie,
  g.max_rental_duration,
  (SELECT title FROM film_rental_duration WHERE rental_duration = g.min_rental_duration AND genre = g.genre LIMIT 1) as shortest_movie,
  g.min_rental_duration
FROM
  genre_max_min g
ORDER BY g.genre;
Expected SQL Query:
WITH film_durations AS (
    SELECT 
        c.name AS category_name, 
        f.title, 
        f.rental_duration,
        RANK() OVER (PARTITION BY c.name ORDER BY f.rental_duration DESC) AS longest_rank,
        RANK() OVER (PARTITION BY c.name ORDER BY f.rental_duration ASC) AS shortest_rank
    FROM 
        film f
        JOIN film_category fc ON f.film_id = fc.film_id
        JOIN category c ON fc.category_id = c.category_id
)
SELECT 
    category_name, 
    title, 
    rental_duration
FROM 
    film_durations
WHERE 
    longest_rank = 1 OR shortest_rank = 1
ORDER BY 
    category_name, rental_duration DESC;

Question: Are there movies that have been rented a lot but always returned on time?
Generated SQL Query:
SELECT f.title, combined.rentals_count
FROM film f
JOIN (
    SELECT f.film_id, COUNT(r.rental_id) AS rentals_count
    FROM film f
    JOIN inventory i ON f.film_id = i.film_id
    JOIN rental r ON i.inventory_id = r.inventory_id
    WHERE r.return_date <= r.rental_date + f.rental_duration * INTERVAL '1 day'
    GROUP BY f.film_id
    HAVING COUNT(r.rental_id) >= 100 -- Adjust threshold as needed
) AS combined ON f.film_id = combined.film_id
ORDER BY combined.rentals_count DESC;
